#Time Series Analysis

## Industrial Gas Production & Garden Equipment Sales Forecasting

This project was conducted as part of the **Time Series Analysis** course at **ESEN (École Supérieure d'Économie Numérique)**.

The objective is to analyze, model, and forecast two monthly economic time series using statistical techniques and ARIMA models.

---

## 🎯 Objectives

* Explore temporal patterns
* Identify trend and seasonality
* Test stationarity
* Build ARIMA forecasting models
* Evaluate model performance
* Generate future forecasts

---

## 📂 Datasets

### 🔥 Industrial Production: Electric and Gas Utilities

* Source: FRED (Federal Reserve Economic Data)
* Series ID: IPG2211A2N
* Period: Jan 1990 – Mar 2024
* Observations: 411

### 🌿 Building Materials & Garden Equipment Sales

* Source: U.S. Census Bureau
* NAICS Code: 444
* Period: Jan 1992 – Dec 2024
* Observations: 387

---

## 🛠️ Technologies

* R
* R Markdown
* Excel
* Forecast Package
* Tseries Package

---

## 🔬 Methodology

### Exploratory Analysis

* Time series visualization
* Descriptive statistics
* Seasonal decomposition
* Monthly boxplots
* ACF analysis
* ADF stationarity test

### Modeling

* Trend estimation
* Seasonal harmonic modeling
* ARIMA model selection
* Residual diagnostics

### Forecasting

* 24-month forecasts
* Confidence intervals
* Model evaluation

---

## 📈 Results

| Metric      | Gas Production     | Garden Equipment Sales |
| ----------- | ------------------ | ---------------------- |
| Model Type  | Additive           | Multiplicative         |
| Adjusted R² | 0.854              | 0.879                  |
| ARIMA Model | (0,1,3)(0,1,1)[12] | (3,0,0)(0,1,2)[12]     |
| AIC         | 1942.08            | 6311.34                |

### Key Findings

* Both series exhibit strong annual seasonality.
* Both datasets are non-stationary before differencing.
* Gas production shows additive seasonality.
* Garden sales exhibit multiplicative seasonality.
* ARIMA models provide accurate forecasting performance.

